**********************************************************
How Indonesian Instant Noodles Became a Nigerian Sensation
**********************************************************

Despite the area cuisine not being particularly known for wheat, Indonesia =
is the world's second biggest consumer of instant noodles. In 2023, they at=
e 14.5 billion servings according to the World Instant Noodles Association.=
 99% of its 285 million people have eaten it at one time or the other. Ther=
e is another name on this list that kind of sticks out: Nigeria. What? Turn=
s out - and this came as a surprise to me too - but the Indonesian noodle b=
rand Indomie is super popular there. It is likely the single most popular p=
ackaged food in all of Africa. So popular it occasionally shows up in rap l=
yrics. How did that happen? In this video, we look at how a noodle brand fr=
om Indonesia became a sensation in Nigeria and the rest of Africa.

----------
Beginnings
----------

I briefly touched upon Indomie's origins in an earlier video on Indonesia's=
 Salim Group. I must admit something. When I made that video, I had never e=
aten or even heard of Indomie. It was just a vaguely familiar Indonesian no=
odle I might have seen somewhere. Turns out it is quite popular! And this v=
ideo is not sponsored by Indomie - they seem to prefer the Kpop band New Je=
ans than Asianometry. Anyway, as mentioned in that video, Indomie's dominan=
t position today dates to Indonesia's authoritarian second President Suhart=
o. Suharto frequently partnered with Chinese entrepreneurs to industrialize=
 his economy and finance his activities. These entrepreneurs often themselv=
es became quite wealthy. The most famous of them was Liem Sioe Liong or Sud=
ono Salim, and his Salim Group business group. At its peak, the group was a=
n Indonesian chaebol with assets worth over $20 billion. But that is a diff=
erent story. Back to noodles. In 1967, Suharto asked the US government to p=
rovide some food aid in the form of rice. The United States and Australia d=
id not have much rice at the time, so they sent wheat instead. Raw wheat ha=
d to be milled before it could be used. But Indonesia did not have any mill=
ing facilities, so the wheat had to be milled in Singapore. This was not id=
eal. Salim, knowing nothing about wheat, went to the legendary Malaysian Ch=
inese tycoon Robert Kuok for advice some time in late 1969. Kuok, whose own=
 business empire included flour mills in Malaysia, told Salim that they sho=
uld just build the mills right in Indonesia. Salim already owned a piece of=
 swampy land along Jakarta Bay for this, and the two partnered in 1969 to f=
ound Bogasari Flour Mills. Bogasari quickly became the dominant flour mille=
r in Indonesia, having received a concession to provide flour to the Java a=
nd Sumatra regions. For his part, Suharto in a 1995 interview claimed that =
it was he who told Salim to build the flour mills. According to him, Salim =
was nothing more than the guy who carried out the order. Robert Kuok receiv=
ed a 25% share in Bogasari, but lost that a few years later when Sudono Sal=
im merged the Bogasari entity into his Indocement company. Kuok was not hap=
py about that. He thought he got flushed out.

-------------------------
Instant Noodles & Indomie
-------------------------

Instant noodles were first popularized by the Taiwanese-Japanese entreprene=
ur Momofuku Ando. In the wake of World War II, Ando pioneered the flash-fry=
ing method for pre-cooking instant noodles. He started selling chicken-flav=
or instant noodle packs and founded a company called Nissin. Today Nissin i=
s the second largest noodle giant by revenue. In 1972, an Indonesian entrep=
reneur from North Sumatra named Djajadi Djaja founded a company called Indo=
mie. The name was in the same style as like the aforementioned Indocement c=
ompany. "Mie" means noodles, so Indomie just means "Indonesian Noodles". In=
domie was not Indonesia's first instant noodle brand. The Supermi brand lau=
nched two years earlier with technical help from the Japanese. But Supermi =
used imported flour to make their noodles. Indomie on the other hand bought=
 their flour at cheaper prices locally from Bogasari.

---------------------
From Flour to Noodles
---------------------

For a while after building this massive flour milling business, Salim did n=
ot do much with it. Salim Group simply sold the flour to noodle and bread-m=
akers. And that was fine, because the Indonesians were not particularly par=
tial to wheat. They liked rice, which is fair because rice is awesome. But =
during a rice shortage in the late 1970s, the Indonesian government asked B=
ogasari to provide and promote an alternative food for its military and civ=
il officials such that rice can be spared for the public. So Bogasari bough=
t a lot of expensive instant noodle machinery to supply the government and =
ran marketing campaigns extolling the virtues of flour-based products like =
bread and noodles. Rice sucked. Eat bread. But the rice shortage situation =
reversed in the 1980s thanks to new strains, good weather, and fertilizers.=
 Green Revolution and all that. Indonesia's rice self-sufficiency was an in=
credible economic achievement, but a business problem for Bogasari Flour. B=
ogasari bought capacity for 2 billion packs of instant noodles each year wi=
th the intention of selling it to the government. But now the government di=
d not want to buy and Bogasari had to do something about this excess capaci=
ty. So they started an instant noodle brand called Sarimi, directly competi=
ng with their customer Indomie. Salim's son Anthony later claimed that they=
 first asked Djajadi if he wanted to buy those lines, but were refused sinc=
e the lines were so different. Whatever the situation, Sarimi noodles quick=
ly won 40% of the market thanks to low production costs from an integrated =
milling business as well as a $10 million marketing campaign. Salim went to=
 Djajadi once more. Djajadi realized the situation and in 1984 merged Sarim=
i and Indomie together to create a JV called Indofood. A few years later, I=
ndofood bought Supermi too, quickly consolidating the Indonesian instant no=
odle market. Initially, Salim owned just 42.5% of the JV. A few years later=
, they bought the rest of the shares from Djajadi. How? Anthony simply said=
 that a few things happened on the other side and they "picked up the piece=
s". Djajadi believed differently, feeling that he had been forced to sell a=
fter going into debt. After Suharto's fall, Djajadi sued Indofood for compe=
nsation. After a seven year saga, the Indonesian Supreme Court eventually d=
ecided against him.

-------------
Spreading Out
-------------

For years after its launch in the early 1970s, Indomie mostly sold in a sou=
p format, kind of like Japanese ramen. Then in 1982, Indomie launched a sou=
p-less dry version called Mi Goreng, which simply means "fried noodles". Th=
is dry version was an instant hit - apparently because it was easier to pre=
pare than the soup version. By 1994, Indofood controlled about 80% of the I=
ndonesian instant noodles market through its three brands - Indomie leading=
 with 60% share and then Supermi and Sarimi. Instant noodles are very cheap=
, easy to cook, and taste great, thanks to MSG. How healthy they are remain=
s somewhat up for debate - okay, maybe not really - but these other things =
we cannot deny. The cheap price is pretty important. Urban dwellers frequen=
tly eat Indomie Sayur, meaning Indomie with a tiny bit of green vegetables,=
 as a complete meal. To accommodate the country's staggering diversity, Ind=
ofood sells over 110 flavors - though Mi Goreng remains the most popular by=
 far. And Indomie is also halal, which matters in the world=E2=80=99s large=
st Muslim population. In the late 1980s, Indomie noodles started going abro=
ad. It seems to have started out as a word-of-mouth thing, Indonesian forei=
gn workers bringing it with them abroad. But over time Indofood caught on, =
striking partnerships with local companies. Indomie has arguably made the m=
ost progress in the Middle East and Africa, where I suspect their halal sta=
tus helps. In Saudi Arabia, their current share of the instant noodle marke=
t is claimed to be over 95%. And there is an Indomie factory in Syria. Some=
what surprisingly it has stayed open throughout that country's long running=
 civil war - providing cheap food for the locals. Several times, the factor=
y almost closed due to high import costs, but the government repeatedly ste=
pped in to get things back up and running. But it is in Africa's most popul=
ous country that Indomie has really made perhaps its most significant impac=
t. And with that, I think it=E2=80=99s now time to chat about Nigeria.

-------
Nigeria
-------

I have not mentioned Nigeria much before on this channel so maybe we can do=
 a quick overview of their cuisine. But first I should point out that Niger=
ia, like Indonesia, is a highly diverse country with over 500 ethnolinguist=
ic groups. So what follows is a gross generalization. Nigeria is warm and t=
ropical. Its agriculture is amenable to growing fruits, cotton, palm trees,=
 pineapple, watermelon, mango, banana, cocoa, peanuts and dates. So the loc=
al cuisine blends indigenous carbohydrates like yams and cassava with beans=
 and local meats to make various delicious salads, snacks, soups, puddings =
and heavy sauces. This cuisine has been influenced by the area's colonial h=
istory - first, the Portuguese and then the British. These influences added=
 New World vegetables, curry, potatoes, and chicken. For example, the addit=
ion of tomatoes and curry powder to a local rice dish called Jollof Rice. W=
hat there is not however, is wheat, and with that wheat-based noodles. And =
yet today, Nigerians love instant noodles. In 2023, they consumed about 3 b=
illion servings of it. So how did Indomie make their way into the country?

-----------------------
From India to Indonesia
-----------------------

In the early 1920s, Khanchand Vaswani, the youngest son of a well-regarded =
physician named Seth Tolaram traveled from British India to Indonesia. The =
family hailed from the northern British Indian province of Sindh. It was tr=
aditional for Sindhi men to go overseas for trade - following the trade rou=
tes of the British Empire. So Vaswani worked with his brothers in Indonesia=
 for a bit before returning. Then came the chaos of the Partition of India.=
 The Sindh province became a part of Pakistan. With large scale violence br=
eaking out, Vaswani and his family fled with only what they had in hand. Hi=
s daughter simply remembers them locking the bungalow and leaving. They wou=
ld never come back. They chartered a bus and traveled to Karachi, and then =
from there took a ship to Mumbai. They stayed at a refugee camp there in Mu=
mbai for a few months. Then they went to what is now the city of Chennai be=
fore connecting to Singapore. There in Singapore, the local Sindh Merchants=
 Association helped arrange passage to the city of Surabaya in Indonesia in=
 March 1948. In the nearby city of Malang, Vaswani founded a textiles shop =
called Toko Vaswani, selling and trading fabrics. In 1950, the company adop=
ted the name of the family patriarch to become the Tolaram Corporation - ex=
panding into chain retail, selling garments and home fabrics.

-----------------------
The Tolaram Corporation
-----------------------

They grew very well by sourcing product in bulk directly from the manufactu=
rers, giving them a price advantage. Their stores put their cheapest textil=
es - the stuff used for school uniforms and such - in the back. Parents wal=
king to go get that often saw other, more expensive things on the way like =
wool and bought that. In the late 1960s, the company opened a small procure=
ment center in Singapore. Then in 1975, they moved their headquarters there=
 as it better suited their international trading operations. Gradually the =
company diversified their product lineup - entering into pulp, chemicals, a=
nd paper products. They also had stakes in factories all around the world f=
rom Estonia to Latvia to South Africa to the United States. In 1977, a Sind=
hi merchant friend suggested to Mohan Vaswani, son of founder Khanchand, to=
 go to Africa. After spending time in Nigeria, Ivory Coast, and Ghana, Moha=
n decided to open shop in Nigeria because of their high population, relativ=
ely higher per capita income, and a lack of consumer electronics. Thusly, T=
olaram became one of the first Singaporean companies to do business in Nige=
ria, trading electronics, textiles and fishing nets. It was a bit of a risk=
y time in Nigeria's history to do business. The country was then under the =
rule of its military after a succession of coups. Then in the early 1980s, =
the economy fell into a foreign exchange crisis due to high spending and a =
shortfall in oil revenues. But being a private company still run and contro=
lled by its founding family, Tolaram can afford to invest for the long term=
. Their first textile factory in Nigeria lost money for almost nine straigh=
t years.

------------------
Indomie in Nigeria
------------------

In 1988, having already been in Nigeria for over a decade, Tolaram began im=
porting noodles from Indofood to Nigeria. The idea to do so came from Hares=
h Aswani, who first joined the company in the 1980s. Aswani and his brother=
 Sajen had seen Indomie's massive success in Indonesia and thought that the=
y can replicate that success in Nigeria too. Nigeria's population seemed si=
milar to Indonesia's. The population was young - average age was like 16. A=
nd it was not only growing very fast - 3% a year - but also becoming increa=
singly more urban - 23% in 1981 and 28% in 1988. But on the other hand. 50%=
 of the Nigerian population did not have access to drinkable water. And 78%=
 lived on less than $2 a day, though noodles were priced to be pretty cheap=
. So Tolaram started by positioning Indomie as a food for kids. At the time=
, the average Nigerian family had five children. So the thinking was that b=
usy mothers entering the workforce can buy Indomie noodles as a cheap but s=
tomach-filling food for their kids. Things got off to a rough start. Nigeri=
ans had no idea what to make of this food. They initially thought that they=
 were being sold worms. And since they are used to eating with their hands,=
 they didn't know how to eat the noodles, let alone cook them. An advertisi=
ng agency finally told them that they had first educate people on the basic=
s. So Tolaram hired people to go to the supermarkets and schools to demonst=
rate. Open the packet. Add 2 cups of water. Boil it and remove the water. T=
hen add seasoning. They hired people to walk onto the streets during Nigeri=
a's legendarily bad traffic jams and demonstrate Indomie. Nevertheless, for=
 the first six years after market entry in 1988, sales volumes of Indomie n=
oodle packs in Nigeria did not really set the world on fire.

-----------
Going Local
-----------

Nevertheless, management still believed in the product and so they doubled =
down. They looked at ways to cut expenses. About 40% of Tolaram's cost of t=
he product was in freight, and they were importing 40-50 containers a month=
. It made sense to skip all that and make product inside the country. In 19=
95, the company struck a deal with Indofood to create a joint venture calle=
d De United Foods - receiving the right to manufacture, brand and sell Indo=
mie noodles in all of West Africa. With this, Tolaram built their first noo=
dle factory in the country. But the joint venture still lost money for seve=
ral years after that. It got to the point that Indofood apparently lost fai=
th and tried to pull out. But Tolaram asked for another year. And then in J=
une 2000, they launched a new flavor, Onion Chicken, along with a massive m=
arketing promotion with giveaways and raffles. Onion chicken was a massive =
hit. Them and other flavors like Pepper Chicken and Jollof catapulted Indom=
ie to the most popular noodle brand in Nigeria, ahead of competitors like C=
hikki or Oh! Noodles! It took 10 years for Indomie noodles to become profit=
able and 12 years to make more than $10 million in revenue. After that thou=
gh, sales started doubling each year. By 2004, they had a second plant and =
producing 40 million noodle packs each month. By 2010, a billion packs a mo=
nth. Today, there are over half a dozen plants around Africa, producing noo=
dles not only for people in Nigeria but also in Ghana, Egypt and Eswatini. =
And despite there being 17+ new competitors in the market, Indomie remains =
dominant.

----------------
A Consumer Giant
----------------

Indomie's success starting in 2000 launched the company onto a different pa=
th. The Asian Financial Crisis of 1997 and the rise of China convinced Tola=
ram that selling B2B commodity products had no future. They decided to scal=
e down almost all their other existing businesses like electronics assembly=
 and textiles so they can grow their consumer brands. This required a great=
 deal of investment. In the late 2000s, suppliers started to fall short in =
delivering noodle raw ingredients. So Tolaram started vertically integratin=
g - opening up their own packaging plant, seasoning plants, flour mills, an=
d oil mills. And it goes deeper than that. Nigeria's infrastructure was the=
n very poor. Just 18% of the roads were paved then. And 75% of their trains=
 did not work. So Tolaram had to "pull in" basic things other companies tak=
e for granted like electricity, water, and waste processing. Tolaram's long=
 term commitment to and experience operating in Nigeria - particularly thei=
r formidable distribution company Multipro - makes them an ideal platform f=
or other consumer brands. In 2015, they struck a joint venture agreement wi=
th Kellogg to bring Kellogg breakfast cereals and snacks to West Africa. As=
 well as another joint venture agreement with Arla, a Danish-Swedish dairy =
cooperative to bring dairy products to Nigeria. Milk and cereal. I can tast=
e the synergies. In 2019, they partnered with Colgate-Palmolive on a joint =
venture to bring dental health products to the Nigerian market. In June 202=
4, they acquired a majority stake in the Guinness Nigeria Brewery from its =
former owner Diageo. Guinness had been having hard times there since SABMil=
ler entered the Nigerian market and started competing heavily with them.

----------
Conclusion
----------

Before we conclude I want to thank viewer of the channel Michael O. in Nige=
ria for recommending this topic. Never knew that I had any kind of viewersh=
ip in Africa. It always tickles me to hear from people of countries so far =
away. In addition to its consumer business, the Tolaram Group has been buil=
ding one of West Africa's biggest infrastructure and real estate projects. =
In 2019, they raised about a billion dollars from China Development Bank an=
d China Harbor Engineering to build the Lekki Deep Sea Port on the outskirt=
s of Lagos. The port can handle some of the largest container ships in the =
world, with TEUs of up to 18,000. The Tolaram company received a 45-year co=
ncession from the Nigerian government and hopes to make the port as signifi=
cant as the ones in Singapore or Dubai. Tolaram's intention is to make the =
Port the core of a larger industrial ecosystem called the Lagos Free Zone. =
The Free Zone is a privately owned free trade zone, where foreign companies=
 can bring their imported goods to sell to the rest of Nigeria. A fascinati=
ng business trajectory and story that has taken us from Indonesia to India =
to Indonesia and then to Nigeria. And at the heart of it all, some 20-cent =
per pack instant noodles.

